        <!-- main heading --> 
        <h1>State of the Union 2015: Five Key Points About the Job Market</h1> 
        <p class="intro"></p>
        <p>Jobs, education, and the economy are expected to be major themes for President Obama’s State of the Union address. At Burning Glass, we’ve collected research that sheds light on some of the most notable—and sometimes overlooked—trends we’ve seen in the labor market.</p>
        <p></p> 
        <div>
         <h2>Five key points to consider about the job market</h2> 
         <p>&nbsp;</p> 
         <p><strong>The impact of "upcredentialing"</strong> Employers increasingly request a bachelor degree for many jobs which have historically&nbsp;been middle skill roles (those requiring more than a high school diploma but less than a B.A.). This means that the job market is in danger of leaving behind many of the two-thirds of Americans who do not have a college degree. (Find out more in our<a href="/research/credentials-gap/" title="Credentials Gap"> "Moving the Goalposts" report</a>).</p> 
         <p>&nbsp;<img src="/media/4530/credentials_gap_chart_500x448.jpg" width="500" height="448" alt="Credentials _gap _chart"></p> 
         <p><strong>This trend actually costs employers time and money.</strong> &nbsp;In some cases, jobs have become more complex and require more education, while in others employers are using the bachelor's degree as a rough screen for skilled applicants. Yet middle skills jobs which require a bachelor’s degree often take longer to fill.&nbsp;(Find out more in our <a href="/research/credentials-gap/" title="Credentials Gap">"Moving the Goalposts" report</a>)</p> 
         <p><img src="/media/4535/average_time_to_fill_chart_500x378.jpg" width="500" height="378" alt="Average _time _to _fill _chart"></p> 
         <p><strong>Information Technology is one of the best opportunities for middle-skill workers.</strong> Middle-skill jobs have historically been blue-collar, but that has changed. IT jobs represent the changing face of middle-skill roles and offer some of the strongest opportunities for middle-skill workers. Over the last 90 days, there were 102,538 online job postings for middle-skill IT jobs, constituting 19% of all IT job postings, and these jobs pay a strong median salary of $57,998.&nbsp;(<a href="/research/middle-skills/" title="Middle Skills">Find out more in the "Bridge the Gap" report </a>we produced in partnership with Harvard Business School and Accenture)</p> 
         <p><strong><img src="/media/6314/Distribution_MiddleSkill_Demand_last_90_Days_499x410.jpg" width="499" height="410" alt="Distribution _Middle Skill _Demand _last _90_Days"></strong></p> 
         <p><strong><strong>Cybersecurity is booming:</strong>&nbsp;</strong>Jobs in this field are outpacing supply. Job postings have grown 74% between 2007-2013, twice as fast as other IT jobs, and cybersecurity jobs carry a $15,000 salary premium. (Find out more in our<a href="/research/cybersecurity/" title="Cybersecurity">&nbsp;report on "The Skills Gap in Cybersecurity.</a>"</p> 
         <p><strong>The paradox of production jobs</strong>: Production jobs, crucial to America’s manufacturing sector, continue their post-recession recovery. Yet many high-skilled production jobs – such as CNC Programmers and Engineering Technicians – are going unfilled as employers struggle to find workers. Although there are fewer production jobs overall, the job market is much tighter for skilled production work. For each skilled production opening, employers are recruiting from an experienced labor pool only one-third the size of that for less-specialized production roles, and postings for skilled production jobs remain open 10% longer than those of their general production counterparts.&nbsp;(Find out more in our<a href="/research/production-skills-gap/" title="Production Skills Gap"> report on "The Skills Gap in Production Roles."</a>)</p> 
         <p>&nbsp;</p>
        </div> 
